Rating: 4
This is a really great tasting and simple recipe. I've made this several times and tried a few different things. First, the deglazing with white wine is excellent. I've tried this with cherry, grape, and roma tomato, and so far grape is probably my favorite. To save time and also add a little extra flavor, I use a pre-made olive tapenade in place of the kalamata olives. It's already pre-chopped, has a nice blend of olive varieties, is easy to measure out, and has other herbs in the tapenade that adds a more complex flavor. It's easy enough to find in most delis. I get the one at Costco and keep it in the back of my fridge just so I can always make this when I'm not in the mood to make something really elaborate. I've also tried adding a variety of other vegetables such as asparagus, green beans, and snow peas so the sauce would be a little more substantial. For the tilapia, I recommed making a very light crust. I first grind salt and pepper over both sides of the fish. Then I mixed together a little cornstarch, fresh ground pepper, and salt and dredged the fillets through that. You won't need a lot. Make sure to shake off the excess starch before searing in the pan. The cornstarch forms a nice crust that helps hold in the moisture and keeps the fish from crumbling into unrecognizable pieces when you place it back in to the sauce to simmer near the end. I've also tried making this with salmon for those who like a fish with a stronger flavor. When using salmon I make a simple herb crust ans sear it in the pan than serve it on a bed of the pasta and sauce rather than cooking the salmon in the sauce itself. I've also tried substituting chicken and apple sausage for the fish and that's worked out well. This last time, I added cooked pasta shells into the sauce and let it simmer awhile so the pasta really picked up the flavors.

